SIMPLE: rafter
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rafter
<hw>Raft"er</hw> <pr>(r⟦adot⟧ft"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A
raftsman.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rafter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rafter
<hw>Raft"er</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>r⟦ae⟧fter</ets>; akin to
E. <ets>raft</ets>, n. See <er>Raft</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>
<def>Originally, any rough and somewhat heavy piece of timber. Now,
commonly, one of the timbers of a roof which are put on sloping,
according to the inclination of the roof. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of
<er>Queen-post</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Courtesy] oft is sooner found in lowly sheds,⟦br⟧
With smoky <qex>rafters</qex>, than in tapestry halls.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rafter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Rafter
<hw>Raft"er</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make into
rafters, as timber.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To furnish with rafters, as a house.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Agric.)</fld> <def>To plow so as to turn the grass
side of each furrow upon an unplowed ridge; to ridge.</def>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rafting</ent>⟦br⟧
